observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

a. direct the  OIC-Municipal Accountant to (i) ensure compliance with Section 20, Volume 1 of the MNGAS for LGUs in the setting up of RPT/SET Receivables;

(ii) reconcile the RPT/SET Receivable accounts with the Municipal Treasurer’s Certified List of Delinquent Real Property Taxpayers and make the necessary adjustments, if any, to present the financial statements fairly;




(iii) require the Municipal Treasurer’s Office (MTO) to provide the Certified List of Delinquent Real Property Taxpayers to the Municipal Accountant’s Office (MAO) at the beginning of the year for setting up the RPT/SET Receivable and at the end of the year for reconciliation; and

(iv) provide the details of the adjustments for RPT/SET Receivables and make sure that every adjusting entry made is supported by an explanation, computation, and/or documentation;


b. instruct the Municipal Assessor to (i) strictly comply with the MRPAAO in the conduct of frequent physical surveys and maintaining records such as Assessment Roll; and


(ii) consider implementing a computerized system to streamline the assessment and collection processes, reduce errors, and increase efficiency; and


c. through the MTO, to exert additional effort to improve collection of fees relative to RPT and SET.

We reiterated that the Municipal Mayor (a) instruct the Municipal Administrator to relinquish the authority/ responsibility to submit the monthly accounts and reports to the MAO;


(b) transfer/reassign the personnel in charge of the so-called “Accounting Office Extension” under the Mayor’s Office to the MAO to augment the workforce thereat; and

(c) direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to adhere strictly to the timeframes on the submission of accounts and preparation of financial reports pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-006; otherwise, withhold the salaries of officials/ employees who continually neglected to abide by the rules and regulations of Section 122 of P.D. No. 1445.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

a. direct the LDRRM Officer and Head of SPOSO to optimize the utilization of the LDRRMF in accordance with the programmed projects in the LDRRMFIP; 

b. instruct the (i) Municipal Health Officer and General Services Officer to submit the distribution lists for COVID-19 and Dengue Rapid Antigen Test Kits; and

(ii) establish stronger protocols for inventory management, distribution tracking, and reporting of supplies/PPEs charged against the LDRRMF to enhance transparency and facilitate better decision-making;

c. instruct the Head of SPOSO to maintain a repair and maintenance/history of each LDRRM vehicle to avoid unnecessary repair and maintenance expenses. A repair history form may be devised, indicating the type of repair undertaken, the date when it was made, and other pertinent data necessary for the information and guidance of the COA, Agency and others concerned and attached the same to the DVs for repairs and maintenance expenses as supporting documents;

d. require the BAC to (i) adopt public bidding as the primary mode of procurement and proceed to alternative methods only when the required conditions are met; and

(ii) stop the practice of splitting purchase requisitions and purchase orders/contracts and adhere to the rules and regulations in the procurement of capital assets, goods, and services as provided under the Updated 2016 RIRR of R.A. No. 9184;

e. (i) consider hiring additional staff dedicated to medical supply inventory management and provide them with computers/laptops for faster updating of medical supplies records to improve efficiency, effectiveness, and response time in managing medical supplies, ensuring optimal care for the community during emergencies; and

(ii) require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to record purchased supplies to its respective inventory account following the perpetual inventory method; and

f. instruct the (i) Municipal Social Welfare and Development Officer to provide the list of recipients with their signature and other documents supporting the distribution of relief goods; and

(ii) OIC-Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer to diligently prepare/maintain inventory records such as Supplies Ledger Cards (SLCs), Stock Cards (SCs), Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS), Monthly Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI) for relief goods and Inventory List of all procured and donated items for LDRRM.

5.29.	We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
MA and GSO Head to (i) reconcile the noted discrepancy of ₱364,176,106.31; (ii) prepare and maintain PPELCs and PCs for each class/type of PPE; and (iii) instruct the IC to coordinate with the MAO and GSO in strategizing the conduct of complete physical inventory in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006;
MA to (i) disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements those contingent assets such as donated lots that are still in the process of transferring title to the Municipality and recognize donated laptops in the books; and (ii) recognize Impairment Loss for unserviceable properties;
GSO Head, in coordination with the IC, to comply with the requirements on the disposal of unserviceable properties;
MA to reclassify CIP accounts to their corresponding PPE accounts upon project completion including the recognition of depreciation expenses and record projects in CIP based on the percentage of completion if not yet completed; and
GSO Head to ensure registration of motor vehicles with LTO to avoid the incurrence of an unnecessary penalty and insure all of its insurable properties to avoid risk in case of damage to, or loss of, its properties due to fire, earthquake, storm, or other casualties.

7.40.	We recommended that Management:
require the Local Development Council to (i) immediately submit the Supplemental AIP related to the additional PPAs appropriated under the Supplemental Budget No. 06 for CY 2023; and (ii) ensure that the 20% DF is utilized to finance the LGU’s priority development projects consistent with its duly approved CDP and updated AIP;
instruct the Municipal Engineer and Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to (i) ensure the effective and efficient implementation of the proposed development projects through adequate planning and close monitoring; and (ii) verify the actual status of completion of projects at year-end to provide reasonably accurate information to the concerned offices/departments;
submit written justification on the continuation of contracts with and non-imposition of liquidated damages to the contractors relative to the projects that incurred negative slippages of more than 15%, as presented in the foregoing discussions;
direct the Municipal Engineer to (i) require the contractors to comply with the prescribed posting of information and publicity on PPAs and inform the AT within ten (10) days after the award of the project or before the start of the PPA that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted at the project site; and (ii) through the conduct of regular inspection, ensure that the information posted in the project signboards are complete, accurate and updated as required by COA Circular No. 2013-004;
instruct the MBO to (i) coordinate with the concerned offices/departments and gather information relevant to the preparation of the 20% DF Utilization Report to ensure accurate and transparent reporting; and (ii) reflect the actual cost incurred of each PPA by considering the percentage of completion at report date prepared and verified by the MEO; and
direct the MA, in coordination with the BAC, to (i) immediately transmit the unsubmitted DVs pertaining to the Fund together with complete supporting documents for prompt verification of the transactions and timely communication to Management of audit deficiencies noted; and (ii) comply with the submission of contracts or POs within five working days from the execution thereof in accordance with Sections 3.1 and 3.2 of COA Circular 2009-001 for the succeeding procurements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) to direct the (a) General Services Officer to (i) exert collaborative effort with the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO) in conducting the activities relative to the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances;




(ii) practice the periodic reconciliation with the accounting records to immediately detect errors/irregularities; and




(iii) secure all the turnover documents of donated properties and submit the same to the Accounting Office;




(b) advise the Municipal Accountant to (i) locate or retrieve the pertinent documents to substantiate the unaccounted balances and take necessary action to establish the accuracy of PPE balances or consider requesting an authority from COA to write off unidentified PPEs or those unsubstantiated beginning balances, provided proper justifications are supported to the request;

(ii) prepare and maintain PPELCs for each type of properties;


(iii) draw Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to record adjustment of the Construction-in-Progress account for completed projects and corresponding Depreciation Expense as recommended;

(iv) coordinate closely with the Municipal Engineering Office to monitor status and progress of projects for purposes of proper accounting; and

(v) secure documents or deeds from the GSO of donated properties and recognize the same in the books of accounts.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to instruct the:

(a) Municipal Accountant to (i) maintain SLCs for each commodity/stock;




(ii) record all purchases of inventory supplies in the books of accounts using the Perpetual Inventory System;




(iii) use the moving average method for costing inventories on monthly reports;




(iv) recognize existing unused supplies based on the result of physical count; and




(v) provide adequate disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements on the information relative to donated inventories and supplies; and

(b) GSO (i) maintain stock cards for each item of inventory;




(ii) regularly reconcile the stock cards with the SLCs of the Accounting Unit;




(iii) report the issuances of supplies thru the SSMI which shall be the basis of the Municipal Accountant in recording to appropriate Expenses accounts; and

(iv) conduct physical count of stocks of all supplies and materials, whether acquired through purchase or donation, and submit relative reports to the Office of the Auditor and other offices concerned on a semi-annual basis.

We recommended that the LCE (a) seriously look into the matter and initiate immediate submission to the COA Auditor’s Office of all the disbursement vouchers and supporting documents pertaining to the current and previous years’ disbursements;

(b) instruct the Municipal Administrator and Municipal Engineer (for infrastructure transactions) to relinquish the authority/responsibility to submit the monthly accounts and reports to the Accounting Department under the supervision of the Municipal Accountant;

(c) transfer/reassign the personnel in charge of the so-called “Accounting Office Extension” under the Mayor’s Office to the Office of the Municipal Accountant to augment the workforce thereat; and

(d) sign/approve the DVs and all supporting documents before payments be effected and the DVs/supporting documents already submitted to the Audit Team, otherwise Notice of Suspensions (NS) will be issued by the Audit Team for the DVs without the signature/approval of the LCE.

We recommended that the LCE, through the GAD Focal Person: (a) continuously comply with the GAD mechanisms and processes to sustain the LGU’s critical consciousness in supporting gender and development, women’s empowerment and responding to gender issues in accordance with the provisions of PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC Nos. 2013-01 and 2016-01;

(b) ensure that GAD Accomplishment Report was supported with the requirements mentioned under Section 5.C.8.5 of the PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01; and

(c) limit the reported expenditures for implemented GAD PPAs out of LGU fund only to fairly present the reported disbursements in the GAD-AR.

We recommended that the LCE: (a) through the Municipal Treasurer, adhere to the existing rules and regulations regarding disbursements wherein procurement of goods and services shall be made by check directly in favor of the suppliers/creditors;

(b) require the BAC to strictly comply with the guidelines and procedures in the succeeding emergency procurements; and




(c) instruct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the BAC for the completion and submission of the noted documentary deficiencies and ensure that only DVs with complete documentation are processed and presented for payment.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the:

(a) MDRRMO, Property Officer and other departments/offices concerned to ensure that the provisions in COA Circular No. 2014-002 are strictly observed before the receipt and issuance of the donated items;

(b) Property Officer to (i) maintain the Registry of Donated Relief Goods for DRRM and Inventory List of All Donated Items for DRRM;




(ii) maintain PCs for donated PPE/s; and




(iii) prepare monthly/ quarterly the Report on the Receipt and Distribution/ Utilization/ Issuance of Donated Relief Goods and PPE; and

(c) Municipal Accountant to (i) record in the books the donated PPEs received by the Municipality;




(ii) provide an additional disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements of information pertaining to DRRM particularly the quantity received, issued and balance of donated relief goods; and




(iii) prepare and maintain PPE Ledger Cards for donated PPEs.

9.4	We recommended that Management direct the:
Municipal Treasurer to (i) demand payment of monthly rentals that have remained uncollected as at year-end; and the Market Committee to (i) institute the civil remedies available pursuant to Section 174 of R.A. No. 7160, and (ii) enforce the cancellation of the lease contract/agreement of delinquent lessees and the revocation of their right to occupy the stalls;
Municipal Treasurer to enforce the collection of security deposits based on the contract;
Municipal Engineer to submit a written clarification/justification on the contract of lease between Lea Business Corporation and Pacificfortia Marine Technologies, Inc.;
Market Committee/Municipal Engineer to (i) execute a contract of lease with each stallholder/lessee signed by both parties and notarized for the full protection and interest of the LGU; and (ii) provide copy of lease contracts together with other pertinent documents to support the recording of rental receivables by the Accounting Office;
Business Permit and Licensing Officer to require market stallholders to apply and annually renew Business/Mayor’s Permit; and
OIC-Municipal Accountant to accrue revenues that remained uncollected as at year-end.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to (a) instruct the Municipal Accountant to require the concerned accountable officers to liquidate/submit liquidation reports as soon as the purpose of the cash advances have been accomplished;

(b) implement the withholding of salaries and/or filing of legal actions for non-compliance with the demand letters issued; and


(c) strictly prohibit the grant of new or additional cash advances whenever previous ones have not yet been fully settled.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the:

(a) Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the LSB not later than July 15 of each year the Certified Statements containing the following: (i) actual SEF Income for the immediately preceding fiscal year; (ii) actual SEF income for the first two quarters of the current year; (iii) the estimated SEF income for the last two quarters of the current year; and (iv) the annual estimates for the ensuing year; 

(b) Municipal Local School Board to (i) prepare the SEF budget on or before October 31 of each calendar year using the SEF Budget Preparation Form;




(ii) abide strictly by the provisions of R.A. No. 7160 and DepEd-DBM-DILG Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2017 and Joint Circular No. 2, s. 2020 in the utilization of the SEF;




(iii) stop the practice of payment of Instructional Allowance and Research and Development Allowance without legal basis; and

(iv) ensure that pertinent supporting documents were attached to the claim thereof; and




(c) Municipal Accountant to (i) submit to the Audit Team the DVs and supporting documents for the utilization of the SEF;




(ii) ensure that disbursements charged against the SEF are properly supported with complete documentation; and




(iii) proper recording of expenses to its appropriate expense account is always observed.

We recommended that the LCE direct the:

(a) Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to (i) ensure the effective and efficient implementation of the proposed projects within the set schedule thru close monitoring;

(ii) properly plan the PPAs to be included in the Local Development Plan and consider environmental management projects towards the attainment of desirable socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes as identified under DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1; and

(iii) stop charging expenditures which do not partake the nature of investment or capital expenditures including rendition of general services and payment of salaries and wages;

(b) MPDC, Municipal Development Council and Local Finance Committee to ensure that the projects to be funded by the 20% DF, especially by re-alignment are derived from the local development plans and that PPAs are included in the AIP. In case additional PPAs will be funded by the 20% DF, a supplemental AIP should be prepared;

(c) Municipal Accountant to (i) coordinate with the members of the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and Technical Working Group (TWG) for the completion and submission of the noted documentary deficiencies and ensure that only DVs with complete documentation are processed and presented for payment to establish the legality and proper accountability over financial transactions; and

(ii) submit to the Audit Team the 22 DVs and supporting documents for the utilization of the 20% DF; and

(c) Municipal Budget Officer to unburden the 20% Development Fund with charges for loan amortization and appropriate reasonable amount for the same based on the total regular income of the LGU after deduction of all its statutory and contractual obligations.

We recommended the LCE to:

(a) instruct the MDRRMO, in coordination with the LDRRMC, to (i) revise the MDRRFIP and use the format prescribed in the COA Circular No. 2012-002 which shall include under a separate caption, the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years; and

(ii) regularly update the LDRRMFIP whenever new expenditure items or as the need for revision arises; 

(b) instruct the Municipal Accountant (i) to ensure that all unexpended/unobligated balance of the QRF and the DRRMF-MOOE shall be transferred to the STF under the account “Trust Liability – DRRM”;




(ii) in coordination with the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), to submit the aforementioned required documents immediately to the Office of the Auditor for proper/further evaluation of the transactions; and

(iii) prepare and maintain PPE Ledger Cards and Supplies Ledger Cards for all PPE and relief goods, respectively, procured out of LDRRMF;

(c) fill up the mandatory positions under DRRM Office so that PPAs can be carried out efficiently and effectively;

(d) make sure that the use of 5% LDRRMF is in accordance with the PPAs included in the LDRRMFIP and see to it that proper coordination between different departments/ offices in the utilization of the Fund were observed;

(e) direct the LDRRMC to monitor and evaluate the use of the Fund and to strive for the timely and full implementation of LDRRM-related PPAs to achieve the goals and objective of the fund and the desired benefits;

(f) require the Property Officer to diligently prepare/maintain inventory records such as SCs and PCs, RIS, Monthly Report of Supplies and Materials Issued, and Inventory List of All Procured and Donated Items and coordinate with the Accounting Office for the periodic reconciliation of both inventory records; and 

(g) require the Head of the SPOSO to apply for the necessary fidelity bond as required by the Bureau of Treasury.

We recommended that management direct/instruct the: 

(a) Municipal Accountant to (i) transfer the financial assistance from various NGAs and trust collections from the General Fund to the Trust Fund books in accordance with existing accounting policy;

(ii) locate/trace from previous records/ documents such details needed to account the unutilized fund balances and remit the same accordingly to the source agencies;

(iii) coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer for the return of unused funds to the source agencies (SAs) or to the National Treasury, as the case may be; and


(iv) scrutinize the completeness of supporting documents of claims before releasing the same for payment and prior to the recording of the transactions in the books of accounts;

(b) Municipal Treasurer to draw a check for the remittance of unutilized amount of all completed projects and the remittance of share to the DPWH;


(c) BAC and the TWG to adhere to the documentary requirements in all stages of the bidding processes and submit written justification for the long period of suspension for the construction of the Evacuation Facility; and

(d) Municipal Administrator/ Municipal Engineer to submit the project documents relative to the local access road project.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive undertake the following courses of action:

(a) instruct the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (LDRRMO) to (i) revise the MDRRFIP to include programs, projects and activities (PPAs) to be undertaken out of the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years; and

(ii) ensure that adequate PPAs are programmed in each of the four thematic areas; 


(b) advise the Municipal Accountant to (i) prepare, certify and submit the monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of LDRRMF to the Audit Team on a regular basis;

(ii) transfer the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF of previous years to a Special Trust Fund; and

(iii) submit to the Audit Team all the relative disbursement vouchers and supporting documents for verification;


(c) direct the Municipal Budget Officer to refrain from using LDRRMF for programs/projects/ activities which are not directly related to disaster preparedness, mitigation, response and rescue operations;

(d) coordinate with the Human Resource Management Office (HRMO) and consider filling up the positions under the DRRM Office, if the budget of the Municipality allows; and

(e) apply for the necessary fidelity bond of all officers accountable for DRRM PPEs as required by the Bureau of Treasury.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Environment Management Officer (MENRO) to:

(a) revise and submit immediately the Municipality’s 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan and take necessary action for its immediate approval with the purpose of ensuring its sustainability, viability, effectiveness, and relevance in relation to local and international developments in the field of solid waste management; 

(b) Proceed immediately with the implementation of Safe Closure and Rehabilitation Plan of the controlled dumpsite facility as ordered by the DENR EMB Region III; 

(c) implement stricter control measures on the surroundings of the transfer station in accordance with DENR A.O. No. 2001 -34 dated December 20, 2001, so as to promote a zero waste, smoke-free and healthy environment; and 


(d) Ensure that the existing MRFs of 14 component barangays are fully functional and provide the necessary technical or financial support to the remaining two barangays for the establishment of their own MRFs.

We recommended that management

(a) submit immediately to the Office of the Auditor a copy of Annexes of the Contract of Lease;

(b) ensure that all necessary permits and licenses are secured and all fees and taxes are paid by the lessee; otherwise, issue a closure order to stop the operations of the lessee until it has duly complied with all the necessary requirements;

(c) instruct the Municipal Treasurer to assess all revenues accruing from the lease agreement and demand collection from the lessee; and

(d) submit a written clarification/justification on the noted inconsistencies in the commencement/effectivity date of the Contract of Lease.

